Definition 4. We define inductively how to build a valid signature $\Sigma$ and the category $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma}$ of cwfs with a $\Sigma$-structure and cwf-morphisms that preserve this structure. First, the base case: The empty signature The empty signature $\emptyset$ is valid and $\mathbf{CwF}_{\emptyset}=\mathbf{CwF}$. Assume now that we have defined $\Sigma$ as a valid signature and the associated category $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma}$. Then we can add a new sort symbol, or a new operator symbol, or a new equation, to get a new valid signature, as follows: Adding a sort symbol Let $\Gamma=(\Gamma_{\mathcal{C}})$ be a uniform family of contexts. Then we can extend $\Sigma$ with a new sort symbol $S$ relative to $\Gamma$, to obtain the gat $\Sigma^{\prime}=(\Sigma,(\Gamma,S))$. The objects of $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma^{\prime}}$ are pairs $({\mathcal{C}},S_{{\mathcal{C}}})$, where ${\mathcal{C}}$ is an object of $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma}$ and $S_{{\mathcal{C}}}\in\mathrm{Ty}_{\mathcal{C}}(\Gamma_{{\mathcal{C}}})$. A morphism in $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma^{\prime}}(({\mathcal{C}},S_{{\mathcal{C}}}),(\mathcal{D},% S_{\mathcal{D}}))$ is a morphism $F\in\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma}({\mathcal{C}},\mathcal{D})$ such that $F(S_{\mathcal{C}})=S_{\mathcal{D}}$. Adding an operator symbol If $\Gamma$ is a uniform family of contexts and $A$ a uniform family of types over $\Gamma$, then we can extend $\Sigma$ with a new operator symbol $f$ relative to $\Gamma$ and $A$, to obtain the gat $\Sigma^{\prime}=(\Sigma,(\Gamma,A,f))$. An object of $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma^{\prime}}$ is a pair $({\mathcal{C}},f_{{\mathcal{C}}})$ where ${\mathcal{C}}$ is an object in $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma}$ and $f_{{\mathcal{C}}}\in\mathrm{Tm}_{\mathcal{C}}(\Gamma_{\mathcal{C}},A_{\mathcal% {C}})$. A morphism in $({\mathcal{C}},f_{{\mathcal{C}}})\to(\mathcal{D},f_{\mathcal{D}})$ is a morphism $F\in\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma}({\mathcal{C}},\mathcal{D})$ such that $F(f_{{\mathcal{C}}})=f_{\mathcal{D}}$ Adding an equation If $\Gamma$ is a uniform family of contexts, $A$ is a uniform family of types over $\Gamma$ and $a,a^{\prime}$ are uniform families of terms in $A$, then we can extend $\Sigma$ with a new equation $a=a^{\prime}$, to obtain the gat $\Sigma^{\prime}=(\Sigma,(\Gamma,A,a,a^{\prime}))$. In this case, $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma^{\prime}}$ is a full subcategory of $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma}$. An object ${\mathcal{C}}$ in $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma^{\prime}}$ is an object ${\mathcal{C}}$ of $\mathbf{CwF}_{\Sigma}$ such that $a_{{\mathcal{C}}}=a^{\prime}_{{\mathcal{C}}}$.
Definition 2. A category with families (cwf) consists of the following data: • A category ${\mathcal{C}}$; • A Fam-valued presheaf on ${\mathcal{C}}$, that is, a functor $T:{\mathcal{C}}^{\text{op}}\to\textbf{Fam}$; • A terminal object $1\in{\mathcal{C}}$, and unique maps $\langle\rangle_{\Gamma}\in{\mathcal{C}}(\Gamma,1)$ for all objects $\Gamma$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$; • Operations ${.\,},~{}\langle\_,\_\rangle,~{}\mathrm{p}$ and $\mathrm{q}$ explained in the following paragraphs. These four operations and their associated equations are referred to as context comprehension. We let $\Gamma,\Delta,\ldots$ range over objects of ${\mathcal{C}}$, and refer to them as contexts. We let $\delta,\gamma,\ldots$ range over morphisms, and refer to them as substitutions. We refer to $1$ as the empty context; the terminal maps $\langle\rangle_{\Gamma}$ represent the empty substitutions. If $T(\Gamma)=(U_{x})_{x\in X}$, we write $\mathrm{Ty}(\Gamma)$ for the set $X$. We call the elements of $\mathrm{Ty}(\Gamma)$ types in context $\Gamma$, and let $A,B,C$ range over such types. Furthermore, for $A\in\mathrm{Ty}(\Gamma)$, we write $\mathrm{Tm}(\Gamma,A)$ for the set $U_{A}$ and call the elements of $\mathrm{Tm}(\Gamma,A)$ terms of type $A$ in context $\Gamma$. For $\gamma:\Delta\to\Gamma$, the functorial action of $T$ yields a morphism $T(\gamma)\in\textbf{Fam}\left((\mathrm{Tm}(\Gamma,A))_{A\in\mathrm{Ty}(\Gamma)% },(\mathrm{Tm}(\Delta,B))_{B\in\mathrm{Ty}(\Delta)}\right)$ consisting of a reindexing function $\_\,[\gamma]:\mathrm{Ty}(\Gamma)\to\mathrm{Ty}(\Delta)$ referred to as substitution in types, and for each $A\in\mathrm{Ty}(\Gamma)$ a function $\_\,[\gamma]:\mathrm{Tm}(\Gamma,A)\to\mathrm{Tm}(\Delta,A[\gamma])$, referred to as substitution in terms. Now we turn to the explanation of the operations ${.\,},~{}\langle\_,\_\rangle,~{}\mathrm{p},~{}\mathrm{q}$. Given $\Gamma\in{\mathcal{C}}$, $A\in\mathrm{Ty}(\Gamma)$, $\gamma:\Delta\to\Gamma$, and $a\in\mathrm{Tm}(\Delta,A[\gamma])$, we have $\Gamma.A\in{\mathcal{C}}\quad\qquad\mathrm{p}_{\Gamma,A}:\Gamma.A\to\Gamma% \quad\qquad\mathrm{q}_{\Gamma,A}\in\mathrm{Tm}(\Gamma.A,A[\mathrm{p}_{\Gamma,A% }])\quad\qquad\langle\gamma,a\rangle_{A}:\Delta\to\Gamma.A.$ We call $\Gamma.A$ the extended context and $\langle\gamma,a\rangle_{A}$ the extended substitution. The operations ${.\,},~{}\langle\_,\_\rangle,~{}\mathrm{p},~{}\mathrm{q}$ satisfy the following universal property: $\langle\gamma,a\rangle_{A}$ is the unique substitution satisfying $\mathrm{p}_{\Gamma,A}\circ\langle\gamma,a\rangle_{A}=\gamma\qquad\text{and}% \qquad\mathrm{q}_{\Gamma,A}[\langle\gamma,a\rangle_{A}]=a\,.$ We refer (colloquially) to $\mathrm{p}$ as the first projection, and to $\mathrm{q}$ as the second projection. Note that the first equation implies that $\mathrm{Tm}(\Delta,A[\mathrm{p}_{\Gamma,A}][\langle\gamma,a\rangle])=\mathrm{% Tm}(\Delta,A[\gamma])$ so that $\mathrm{q}_{\Gamma,A}[\langle\gamma,a\rangle]$ and $a$ are elements of the same set. Here and below, subscripts are omitted from ${.\,},~{}\langle\_,\_\rangle,~{}\mathrm{p},~{}\mathrm{q}$ when they can be reconstructed from the context (no pun intended). (End Definition 2.)
Definition 2.5 (Principal $G$-bundle over a Lie groupoid). Let $G$ be a Lie group, and let $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ be a Lie groupoid. A (right) principal $G$-bundle over $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is a (right) principal $G$-bundle $\pi\,\colon\,E_{G}\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}$ over the manifold $X_{0}$ together with a left action $(\pi:E_{G}\rightarrow X_{0},\ \mu\colon X_{1}\times_{s,X_{0},\pi}E_{G}% \rightarrow E_{G}),$ of the Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}$ on the manifold $E_{G}$, such that $(\gamma\cdot p)\cdot g\,=\,\gamma\cdot(p\cdot g)$ for all $(\gamma,\,p,\,g)\,\in\,X_{1}\times_{X_{0}}E_{G}\times G$. Henceforth, we shall often write $\gamma\cdot p$ instead of $\mu(\gamma,\,p)$. A principal $G$-bundle over $\mathbb{X}$ will be denoted as $\bigl{(}E_{G}\rightarrow X_{0},\ [X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]\bigr{)}$. A morphism of principal $G$-bundles from $(E_{G}\rightarrow X_{0},\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}])$ to $(E_{G}^{\prime}\rightarrow X_{0},\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}])$ is a morphism $\psi\,\colon\,(E_{G},\,\pi,\,X_{0})\,\longrightarrow\,(E_{G}^{\prime},\,\pi^{% \prime},\,X_{0})$ of the underlying principal bundles over the manifold $X_{0}$, such that $\psi(\mu(\gamma,\,e))\,=\,\mu^{\prime}(\gamma,\,\psi(e))$ for all $(\gamma,\,e)\,\in\,X_{1}\times_{s,X_{0},a}E_{G}$.
Definition 2.12 (Fibered category). A functor $\pi_{\mathcal{D}}\,:\,(\mathcal{D}\,\longrightarrow\,\mathcal{C})$ is a fibered category over $\mathcal{C}$ if for every $(\eta,f)\,\in\,\mathcal{D}_{0}\times_{\mathcal{C}_{0},t}\mathcal{C}_{1}$ there exists a Cartesian arrow $\theta\,\colon\,\xi\,\longrightarrow\,\eta$ with $\pi_{\mathcal{D}}(\theta)\,=\,f$. We call such $\xi$ to be the pullback of $\eta$ along $f$. A morphism of fibered categories over $\mathcal{C}$ from $(\mathcal{D},\,\pi_{\mathcal{D}},\,\mathcal{C})$ to $(\mathcal{D}^{\prime},\,\pi_{\mathcal{D}^{\prime}},\,\mathcal{C})$ is a functor $F\,\colon\,\mathcal{D}\,\longrightarrow\,\mathcal{D}^{\prime}$ that maps a Cartesian arrow in $\mathcal{D}$ to a Cartesian arrow in $\mathcal{D}^{\prime}$ satisfying $\pi_{\mathcal{D}^{\prime}}\circ F\,=\,\pi_{\mathcal{D}}$.
Definition 3.8 (Horizontal component of a differential form). Let $\varphi\,:\,X_{1}\,\longrightarrow\,\bigwedge^{k}T^{*}X_{1}$ be a differential $k$-form on the manifold $X_{1}$. The horizontal component of $\varphi$ (with respect to the connection $\mathcal{H}$) is the differential $k$-form $\widehat{\mathcal{H}}(\varphi)(\gamma)(v_{1},\,\cdots,\,v_{k})\,=\,\varphi(% \gamma)(P_{\mathcal{H}_{\gamma}}(v_{1}),\,\cdots,\,P_{\mathcal{H}_{\gamma}}(v_% {k}))$ , for all $\gamma\,\in\,X_{1}$ and $v_{i}\,\in\,T_{\gamma}X_{1}$, $1\,\leq\,i\,\leq\,k$, where $P_{\mathcal{H}_{\gamma}}$ is the projection in (3.5).
Definition 2.9 (Vector bundle over a Lie groupoid). Let $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ be a Lie groupoid. A (rank $k$) vector bundle over the Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is a (rank $k$) vector bundle $\pi\,\colon\,E\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}$ over the manifold $X_{0}$ together with a left action $\bigl{(}\pi\,:\,E\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0},\ \mu\,\colon\,X_{1}\times_{s,X_{0},% \pi}E\,\longrightarrow\,E\bigr{)}$ of the Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}$ on $E$ such that the map $\mu_{\gamma}\,\colon\,E_{s(\gamma)}\,\longrightarrow\,E_{t(\gamma)}$, $a\,\longmapsto\,\gamma\cdot a$, is linear for every $\gamma\,\in\,X_{1}$.
Definition 2.16 (Differentiable stack). Let Man be the site with étale topology. A stack $\mathcal{D}\,\longrightarrow\,\text{Man}$ is called a differentiable stack if there exists a Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}$ such that there is an isomorphism of stacks $\mathcal{B}\mathbb{X}\,\cong\,\mathcal{D}$.
Definition 2.1 (Action of a Lie groupoid on a manifold). Let $\mathbb{X}=[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ be a Lie groupoid. Let $P$ be a smooth manifold. A left action of the Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ on the manifold $P$ is given by a pair of smooth maps $a\,\colon\,P\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}\ \ \text{ and }\ \ \mu\,\colon\,X_{1}% \times_{s,X_{0},\pi}P\,\longrightarrow\,P$ satisfying the following conditions: (1) $1_{a(p)}\cdot p\,=\,p$ for all $p\,\in\,P$, (2) $a(\gamma\cdot p)\,=\,t(\gamma)$ for all $(\gamma,\,p)\,\in\,X_{1}\times_{s,X_{0},a}P$, and (3) $\gamma^{\prime}\cdot(\gamma\cdot p)\,=\,(\gamma^{\prime}\circ\gamma)\cdot p$ for all $(\gamma^{\prime},\,\gamma,\,p)\,\in\,X_{1}\times_{s,X_{0},t}X_{1}\times_{s,X_{% 0},\pi}P$.
Definition 3.11. Let $\bigl{(}\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}],\,\mathcal{H}^{\mathbb{X% }}\bigr{)}$ and $\bigl{(}\mathbb{Y}\,=\,[Y_{1}\rightrightarrows Y_{0}],\,\mathcal{H}^{\mathbb{Y% }}\bigr{)}$ be a pair of Lie groupoids equipped with connection. A morphism of Lie groupoids $(F,\,f)\,\colon\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]\,\longrightarrow\,[Y_{1}% \rightrightarrows Y_{0}]$ will be called a morphism of Lie groupoids with connections if $dF(\mathcal{H}^{\mathbb{X}})\,=\,\mathcal{H}^{\mathbb{Y}}\,,$ where $dF$ is the differential of the map $F$. We shall employ the notation $(F,f)\,\colon\,\bigl{(}[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}],\,\mathcal{H}^{\mathbb{X% }}\bigr{)}\,\longrightarrow\,\bigl{(}[Y_{1}\rightrightarrows Y_{0}],\,\mathcal% {H}^{\mathbb{Y}}\bigr{)}$ for such a morphism.
Definition 2.10 (Principal $\mathbb{X}$-bundle over a manifold). Let $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ be a Lie groupoid. Let $M$ be a smooth manifold. A principal (right) $\mathbb{X}$-bundle over $M$ is a surjective submersion $\pi\,\colon\,P\,\longrightarrow\,M$ together with a right action $\bigl{(}a\colon P\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0},\ \mu\colon P\times_{a,X_{0},t}X_{1}% \,\longrightarrow\,P\bigr{)}$ of the Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}$ on the manifold $P$, such that following two conditions are satisfied: (1) $\pi(p\cdot h)\,=\,\pi(p)$ for all $(p,\,h)\,\in\,P\times_{X_{0}}X_{1}$, and (2) the map $P\times_{a,X_{0},t}X_{1}\,\longrightarrow\,P\times_{\pi,M,\pi}P$ given by $(p,\,h)\,\longmapsto\,(p,\,p\cdot h)$ is a diffeomorphism.
Definition 3.9 (Differential forms on a Lie groupoid). A differential $k$-form $\varphi\,\colon\,X_{0}\,\longrightarrow\,\bigwedge^{k}T^{*}X_{0}$ on the manifold $X_{0}$ is said to be a differential $k$-form on $\mathbb{X}$ (with respect to the connection $\mathcal{H}$) if $\widehat{\mathcal{H}}(s^{*}\varphi)\,=\,\widehat{\mathcal{H}}(t^{*}\varphi)\,,$ where $\widehat{\mathcal{H}}$ is constructed as in Definition 3.8.
Definition 2.14 (Stack). Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a site. A fibered category $(\mathcal{D},\,\pi_{\mathcal{D}},\,\mathcal{C})$ is said to be a stack over the site $\mathcal{C}$ if for each object $U$ of $\mathcal{C}$ and a covering $\{U_{\alpha}\rightarrow U\}$ of $U$, the functor defined in (2.3) is an equivalence of categories. A morphism of stacks is a morphism of the underline fibered categories.
Definition 5.5. Let $(E_{G}\rightarrow X_{0},[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}])$ be a principal $G$-bundle over a Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}=[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$. A connection on $(E_{G}\rightarrow X_{0},[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}])$ is a connection $\omega\in{\Omega}^{1}(E_{G},\mathfrak{g})$ on the underline principal $G$-bundle $E_{G}\to X_{0}$ such that, ${\rm pr}_{2}^{*}\omega-\mu^{*}\omega=0$.
Definition 2.11. Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be categories and $\pi_{\mathcal{D}}\,:\,\mathcal{D}\,\longrightarrow\,\mathcal{C}$ be a functor. An arrow $\theta\,\colon\,\xi\,\longrightarrow\,\eta$ in $\mathcal{D}$ is said to be a Cartesian arrow in $\mathcal{D}$ if for every morphism $\theta^{\prime}\,\colon\,\xi^{\prime}\,\longrightarrow\,\eta$ in $\mathcal{D}$, and a morphism $h\,\colon\,\pi_{\mathcal{D}}(\xi^{\prime})\,\longrightarrow\,\pi_{\mathcal{D}}% (\xi)$ in $\mathcal{C}$ with $\pi(\theta)\circ h\,=\,\pi(\theta^{\prime})$, there exists a unique morphism $\Phi\,\colon\,\xi^{\prime}\,\longrightarrow\,\xi$ in $\mathcal{D}$ such that $\theta\circ\Phi\,=\,\theta^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{D}$ and $\pi_{\mathcal{D}}(\Phi)\,=\,h$ in $\mathcal{C}$. We visually represent a Cartesian arrow by the following diagram: $\tikzcd\xi^{\prime}\arrow[rd,"\theta^{\prime}"]\arrow[dd,dotted,"\Phi"]\arrow[% rrr,mapsto]&&&\pi(\xi^{\prime})\arrow[rd,"\pi(\theta^{\prime})"]\arrow[dd,"h"^% {\prime}]&\\ &\eta\arrow[rrr,mapsto]&&&\pi(\eta)\\ \xi\arrow[ru,"\theta"^{\prime}]\arrow[rrr,mapsto]&&&\pi(\xi)\arrow[ru,"\pi(% \theta)"^{\prime}]&.$
Definition 4.2 (Connections on principal bundles over Lie groupoids). Let $\mathcal{H}\,\subset\,TX_{1}$ be a connection on the Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$. Let $\bigl{(}E_{G}\,\rightarrow\,X_{0},\,\,\mathbb{X}\bigr{)}$ be a principal $G$-bundle over $\mathbb{X}$. A connection on $(E_{G}\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0},\,\,\mathbb{X})$ is a splitting of the Atiyah exact sequence in (4.1) of vector bundles over $\mathbb{X}$.
Definition 3.1 (Connection on a Lie groupoid). A connection on a Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is a distribution $\mathcal{H}\,\subset\,TX_{1}$ satisfying the following three conditions: (1) $\mathcal{H}$ is a complement of $ds$, (2) $(de)_{x}(T_{x}X_{0})\,=\,\mathcal{H}_{e(x)}X_{1}$ for all $x\,\in\,X_{0}$, and (3) $\theta_{\gamma}\circ\theta_{\gamma^{\prime}}\,=\theta_{\gamma\circ\gamma^{% \prime}}$ for every composable pair $\gamma,\,\gamma^{\prime}\,\in\,X_{1}$, where $\theta$ is the homomorphism in (3.6). A connection $\mathcal{H}\,\subset\,TX_{1}$ on $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is said to be integrable (or flat) if the distribution $\mathcal{H}$ is integrable.
Definition 1. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be a variety with Boolean factor congruences. We say that $\mathcal{V}$ is stable by complements if every homomorphism preserves complementary central elements.
Definition 2.3 (Stack). A category fibered in groupoids $\mathscr{X}$ over $\mathfrak{S}$ is a stack if the following gluing axioms hold with respect to the site ${\mathfrak{S}}_{et}$: (i) Take any smooth space $X$ in $\mathfrak{S}$, any two objects $x,y$ in ${\mathscr{X}}$ lying over $X$ and any two isomorphisms $\phi\,,\psi\,:\,x\,\longrightarrow\,y$ over $X$. If the condition $\phi|_{U_{i}}\,=\,\psi|_{U_{i}}$ holds for all $U_{i}$ in a covering $\{U_{i}\rightarrow X\}$, then $\phi\,=\,\psi$. (ii) Take any smooth space $X$ in $\mathfrak{S}$, any two objects $x\,,y\,\in\,{\mathscr{X}}$ lying over $X$ and any covering $\{U_{i}\longrightarrow X\}$ with isomorphisms $\phi_{i}\,:\,x|_{U_{i}}\,\longrightarrow\,y|_{U_{i}}$ for every $i$. If the condition $\phi_{i}|_{U_{ij}}\,=\,\phi_{j}|_{U_{ij}}$ holds for all $i,\,j$, then there exists an isomorphism $\phi\,:\,x\,\longrightarrow\,y$ with $\phi|_{U_{i}}\,=\,\phi_{i}$ for all $i$. (iii) For any smooth space $X$ in $\mathfrak{S}$, any covering $\{U_{i}\longrightarrow X\}$, any family $\{x_{i}\}$ of objects $x_{i}$ in the fiber ${\mathscr{X}}_{U_{i}}$ and any family of morphisms $\{\phi_{ij}\}$, where $\phi_{ij}\,:\,x_{i}|_{U_{ij}}\,\longrightarrow\,x_{j}|_{U_{ij}}$ satisfies the cocycle condition $\phi_{jk}\circ\phi_{ij}\,=\,\phi_{ik}$ in ${\mathscr{X}}(U_{ijk})$, there exists an object $x$ lying over $X$ with isomorphisms $\phi_{i}\,:\,x|_{U_{i}}\,\longrightarrow\,x_{i}$ such that $\phi_{ij}\circ\phi_{i}\,=\,\phi_{j}$ in ${\mathscr{X}}(U_{ij})$.
Definition 5.3 (Connection on principal bundle over Lie groupoid). A connection on the principal $G$-bundle ${\mathbb{E}}_{G}\,=\,[Q\rightrightarrows E_{G}]$ over the Lie groupoid ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is a connection $\nabla$ on the principal $G$-bundle $E_{G}\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}$ such that the two $\mathfrak{g}$-valued $1$-forms $\widetilde{s}^{*}\widehat{\nabla}$ and $\widetilde{t}^{*}\widehat{\nabla}$ on $Q$ coincide, where $\widehat{\nabla}$ is the $1$-form $\widehat{\nabla}\,:\,TE_{G}\,\longrightarrow\,\mathfrak{g}$ associated to the connection $\nabla$.
Definition 5.7. For a principal $G$-bundle ${\mathbb{E}}_{G}=[s^{*}E_{G}\rightrightarrows E_{G}]$ over a Lie groupoid ${\mathbb{X}}=[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ with a connection $D$, the section $K(D)$ is called the curvature of the connection $D$.
Definition 2.1 (Category fibred in groupoids). A category fibered in groupoids over $\mathfrak{S}$ is a category $\mathscr{X}$, together with a functor $\pi_{\mathscr{X}}\,:\,\mathscr{X}\,\longrightarrow\,\mathfrak{S}$ satisfying the following axioms: (i) For every morphism $V\longrightarrow U$ in $\mathfrak{S}$, and every object $x$ of $\mathscr{X}$ lying over $U$, there exists an arrow $y\longrightarrow x$ in $\mathscr{X}$ lying over $V\longrightarrow U$, (ii) For every commutative triangle $W\longrightarrow V\longrightarrow U$ in $\mathfrak{S}$ and every morphisms $z\longrightarrow x$ and $y\longrightarrow x$ in $\mathscr{X}$ lying over $W\longrightarrow U$ and $V\longrightarrow U$ respectively, there exists a unique arrow $z\longrightarrow y$ in $\mathscr{X}$ lying over $W\longrightarrow V$ such that the composition $z\longrightarrow y\longrightarrow x$ is the morphism $z\longrightarrow x$.
Definition 2.4 (Differentiable stack). A stack $\mathscr{X}$ over the site $\mathfrak{S}_{et}$ is called differentiable if there exists a smooth space $X$ in $\mathfrak{S}$ and a surjective representable submersion $x\,:\,X\,\longrightarrow\,{\mathscr{X}}$, meaning there exists a smooth space $X$ together with a morphism of stacks $x\,:\,X\,\longrightarrow\,{\mathscr{X}}$, such that for every smooth space $U$ and every morphism of stacks $U\,\longrightarrow\,{\mathscr{X}}$, the following two hold: (1) the fiber product $X\times_{\mathscr{X}}U$ is representable, and (2) the induced morphism of smooth spaces $X\times_{\mathscr{X}}U\,\longrightarrow\,U$ is a surjective submersion.
Definition 2.6 (Lie groupoid). A Lie groupoid $\mathbb{X}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is a groupoid internal to the category $\mathfrak{S}$ of smooth spaces, meaning the space $X_{1}$ of arrows and the space $X_{0}$ of objects are objects of $\mathfrak{S}$ and all structure morphisms $s,\,t\,:\,X_{1}\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}\,,\ \ m\,:\,X_{1}\times_{s,X_{0},t}X_{% 1}\longrightarrow X_{1}\,,$ $i\,:\,X_{1}\,\longrightarrow\,X_{1}\,,\ \ e\,:\,X_{0}\,\longrightarrow\,X_{1}$ are morphisms in $\mathfrak{S}$ (so they are smooth maps). Here $s$ is the source map, $t$ is the target map, $m$ is the multiplication map, $e$ is the identity section, and $i$ is the inversion map of the groupoid. The source map $s$ is a submersion. Using $i$, this implies that the target map $t$ is also a submersion. If $s$ and $t$ are étale, the groupoid ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is called étale. If the anchor map $(s,\,t)\,:\,X_{1}\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}\times X_{0}$ is proper, the groupoid is called a proper groupoid. A Lie group $G$ is a Lie groupoid $[G\rightrightarrows*]$ with one object, meaning the space $X_{0}$ is just a point in $\mathfrak{S}$.
Definition 4.1 (Connection on Lie groupoid). A connection on a Lie groupoid ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is a distribution ${\mathcal{H}}\,\subset\,TX_{1}$ such that (i) for every $x\,\in\,X_{0}$, the image of the differential $de(x)\,:\,T_{x}X_{0}\,\longrightarrow\,T_{e(x)}X_{1}$ coincides with the subspace ${\mathcal{H}}_{e(x)}\,\subset\,T_{e(x)}X_{1}$, and (ii) for every $y\,,z\,\in\,X_{1}$ with $t(y)\,=\,s(z)$, the homomorphism $\theta_{m(z,y)}\,:\,T_{s(y)}X_{0}\,\longrightarrow\,T_{t(z)}X_{0}$ coincides with the composition $\theta_{z}\circ\theta_{y}$ (see (4.4)). A connection on ${\mathbb{X}}$ is said to be flat (or integrable) if the distribution $\mathcal{H}$ defining the connection is integrable.
Definition 5.5. Let $\widehat{\nabla}$ be a connection on a principal $G$-bundle ${\mathbb{E}}_{G}\,=\,[s^{*}E_{G}\rightrightarrows E_{G}]$ over the Lie groupoid ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ given by a connection $\nabla$ on $E_{G}$. The curvature of $\widehat{\nabla}$ is defined to be the curvature of $\nabla$. In particular, the connection $\widehat{\nabla}$ is called flat if $\nabla$ is integrable.
Definition 3.1 (Principal bundle over differentiable stack). Let $G$ be a Lie group and $\mathscr{X}$ a differentiable stack. A principal $G$-bundle or $G$-torsor ${\mathscr{E}}_{G}$ over $\mathscr{X}$ is given by a $2$-Cartesian diagram $\xymatrix{{\mathscr{E}}_{G}\times G\rto^{\sigma}\dto^{p_{1}}&{\mathscr{E}}_{G}% \dto^{\pi}\ar@{=>}[dl]\\ {\mathscr{E}}_{G}\rto^{\pi}&\mathscr{X}.}$ such that for any submersion $f\,:\,U\,\longrightarrow\,\mathscr{X}$ from a smooth space $U$, the pullback by $f$ in the above diagram defines a principal $G$-bundle on $U$. Morphisms $\rho\,:\,{\mathscr{E}}_{G}\,\longrightarrow\,{\mathscr{F}}_{G}$ between two principal $G$-bundles ${\mathscr{E}}_{G}$ and ${\mathscr{F}}_{G}$ are defined in the obvious way.
Definition 5.1. The Atiyah bundle for a principal $G$-bundle $E_{G}$ over $X_{0}$ is the invariant direct image $\text{At}(E_{G})\,:=\,(\alpha_{*}TE_{G})^{G}\,\subset\,\alpha_{*}TE_{G}\,.$
Definition 2.10 (Torsors). Let ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ be a Lie groupoid, and let $S$ be a smooth space. A (right) $\mathbb{X}$-torsor over $S$ is a smooth space $P$ together with a surjective submersion $\pi\,:\,P\,\longrightarrow\,S$ and a right action of $\mathbb{X}$ on $P$ (see the second part of Definition 2.9) satisfying the extra condition that for all $p,\,\,p^{\prime}\,\in\,P$ with $\pi(p)\,=\,\pi(p^{\prime})$, there exists a unique $x\,\in\,X_{1}$ such that $p\cdot x$ is defined and $p\cdot x\,=\,p^{\prime}$. Let $\pi\,:\,P\,\longrightarrow\,S$ and $\rho\,:\,Q\,\longrightarrow\,T$ be $\mathbb{X}$-torsors. A morphism of $\mathbb{X}$-torsors from the first one to the second one is given by a Cartesian diagram of smooth maps $\xy\xymatrix{P\ar[r]^{\varphi}\ar[d]&Q\ar[d]\\ S\ar[r]&T}\endxy$ such that $\varphi$ is a $X_{1}$-equivariant map. Again, there is also a similar notion of a (left) $\mathbb{X}$-torsor over a smooth space $S$. Given a $\mathbb{X}$-torsor $P$, the map $P\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}$ is called the anchor map or momentum map. The surjective submersion $\pi\,:\,P\,\longrightarrow\,S$ is called the structure map.
Definition 4.4 (Connection on differentiable stack). A connection on a differentiable stack ${\mathscr{X}}$ is a connection on a Lie groupoid ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ representing the stack. A connection on ${\mathscr{X}}$ is intgrable or (flat) if the connection on ${\mathbb{X}}$ is flat.
Definition 2.5. A differentiable stack $\mathscr{X}$ is a (proper) Deligne–Mumford stack if it has a (proper) étale presentation.
Definition 3.4 (Principal bundle over Lie groupoid). Let $G$ be a Lie group and ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ a Lie groupoid. A principal $G$-bundle or $G$-torsor over $\mathbb{X}$, denoted by ${\mathbb{E}}_{G}\,:=\,[s^{*}E_{G}\rightrightarrows E_{G}]$, is given by a principal (right) $G$-bundle $\pi\,:\,E_{G}\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}$, which is also a $\mathbb{X}$-space such that for all $x\,\in\,E_{G}$ and all $\gamma\,\in\,X_{1}$ with $s(\gamma)\,=\,\pi(x)$, we have $(\gamma\cdot x)\cdot g\,=\,\gamma\cdot(x\cdot g)~{}\ \mathrm{for\,\,all}~{}\ g% \,\in\,G\,.$ Let $s^{*}E_{G}\,=\,X_{1}\times_{s,X_{0},\pi}E_{G}$ be the pullback along the source map $s$. Then ${\mathbb{E}}_{G}\,=\,[s^{*}E_{G}\rightrightarrows E_{G}]$ is in a natural way a Lie groupoid, the transformation groupoid with respect to the $X_{1}$-action.
Definition 2.9. Let ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ be a Lie groupoid. A (left) $\mathbb{X}$-space is given by an object $P$ of $\mathfrak{S}$ together with a smooth map $\pi\,:\,P\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}$ and a map $\sigma\,:\,Q\,:=\,X_{1}\times_{s,X_{0},\pi}P\,\longrightarrow\,P\,,\ \ ~{}% \sigma(\gamma,\,x)\,:=\,\gamma\cdot x$ such that for all $x\,\in\,P$, (i) $e(\pi(x))\cdot x\,=\,x$, and (ii) $(\delta\cdot\gamma)\cdot x\,=\,\delta\cdot(\gamma\cdot x)$ for all $\gamma\,,\delta\,\in\,X_{1}$ satisfying $t(\gamma)\,=\,s(\delta)$ and $\pi(x)\,=\,s(\gamma)$. Similarly, a (right) $\mathbb{X}$-space is given given by an object $P$ of $\mathfrak{S}$ together with a smooth map $\pi\,:\,P\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}$ and a map $\sigma\,:\,Q\,:=\,P\times_{t,X_{0},\pi}X_{1}\,\longrightarrow\,P\,,\ \ ~{}% \sigma(x,\,\gamma)\,:=\,x\cdot\gamma$ such that for all $x\,\in\,P$, (i) $x\cdot e(\pi(x))\,=\,x$, and (ii) $x\cdot(\delta\cdot\gamma)\,=\,(x\cdot\delta)\cdot\gamma$ for all $\gamma\,,\delta\,\in\,X_{1}$ satisfying $t(\gamma)\,=\,s(\delta)$ and $\pi(x)\,=\,t(\delta)$.
Definition 5.2. A connection on a principal $G$-bundle $E_{G}$ over $X_{0}$ is a splitting of the Atiyah exact sequence $0\,\longrightarrow\,\text{ad}(E_{G})\,\longrightarrow\,\text{At}(E_{G})\,% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle(d\alpha)^{\prime}}}{{\longrightarrow}}\,TX_{0}\,% \longrightarrow\,0\,.$
Definition 2.12. Let ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ and ${\mathbb{Y}}\,=\,[Y_{1}\rightrightarrows Y_{0}]$ be Lie groupoids. A morphism of Lie groupoids is a functor $\phi\,:\,{\mathbb{X}}\,\longrightarrow\,{\mathbb{Y}}$ given by two smooth maps $\phi\,=\,(\phi_{1},\,\phi_{0})$ with $\phi_{0}\,:\,X_{0}\,\longrightarrow\,Y_{0}\,,\ \ \phi_{1}\,:\,X_{1}\,% \longrightarrow\,Y_{1}$ which commute with all structure morphisms of the groupoids. A morphism $\phi\,:\,{\mathbb{X}}\,\longrightarrow\,{\mathbb{Y}}$ of Lie groupoids is a Morita morphism or essential equivalence if (i) $\phi_{0}\,:\,X_{0}\,\longrightarrow\,Y_{0}$ is a surjective submersion, and (ii) the diagram $\xy\xymatrix{X_{1}\ar[r]^{(s,t)}\ar[d]_{\phi_{1}}&X_{0}\times X_{0}\ar[d]^{% \phi_{0}\times\phi_{0}}\\ Y_{1}\ar[r]^{(s,t)}&Y_{0}\times Y_{0}}\endxy$ is Cartesian, or in other words, $X_{1}\,\cong\,Y_{1}\times_{Y_{0}\times Y_{0}}(X_{0}\times X_{0})$. Two Lie groupoids $\mathbb{X}$ and $\mathbb{Y}$ are Morita equivalent, if there exists a third Lie groupoid $\mathbb{W}$ and Morita morphisms ${\mathbb{X}}\,\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi}}{{\longleftarrow}}\,{\mathbb{W}}\,% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle\psi}}{{\longrightarrow}}\,{\mathbb{Y}}\,.$
Definition 5.4. A connection on the principal $G$-bundle ${\mathbb{E}}_{G}\,=\,[s^{*}E_{G}\rightrightarrows E_{G}]$ over the Lie groupoid ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is a connection $\nabla$ on the principal $G$-bundle $E_{G}\,\longrightarrow\,X_{0}$ such that the two $\mathfrak{g}$-valued $1$-forms $\widehat{s}^{*}\widehat{\nabla}$ and $\widehat{t}^{*}\widehat{\nabla}$ on $s^{*}E_{G}$ coincide, where $\widehat{\nabla}$ is the $1$-form $\widehat{\nabla}\,:\,TE_{G}\,\longrightarrow\,\mathfrak{g}$ associated to the connection $\nabla$.
Definition 3.7. Let ${\mathbb{X}}\,=\,[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ be a Lie groupoid and $G$ a Lie group. A principal $G$-groupoid over $\mathbb{X}$ is a Lie groupoid ${\mathbb{P}}\,=\,[Q\rightrightarrows P]$ together with a groupoid morphism $\xymatrix{G\rto&Q\rto^{\tau}\ar@<-2pt>[d]_{\widetilde{t}}\ar@<+2pt>[d]^{% \widetilde{s}}&X_{1}\ar@<-2pt>[d]_{t}\ar@<+2pt>[d]^{s}\\ G\rto&P\rto^{\pi}&X_{0}}$ such that both $G\,\longrightarrow\,Q\,\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\tau}}{{\longrightarrow}}\,X_{1}$ and $G\,\longrightarrow\,P\,\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\pi}}{{\longrightarrow}}\,X_{0}$ are principal $G$-bundles, and, furthermore, the following conditions hold: (1) the source and target maps $\widetilde{s}$ and $\widetilde{t}$ on $Q$ are $G$-equivariant, (2) the identity section $\widetilde{e}\,:\,P\,\longrightarrow\,Q$ is $G$-equivariant, (3) the inversion map $\widetilde{i}\,:\,Q\,\longrightarrow\,Q$ satisfies the identity $\widetilde{i}(zg)\,=\,\widetilde{i}(z)g^{-1}$ for all $z\,\in\,Q$ and $g\,\in\,G$, and (4) the multiplication map $Q\times_{s,X_{0},t}Q\,\longrightarrow\,Q$ is $G$-equivariant for the diagonal action of $G$ on $Q\times_{s,X_{0},t}Q$.
Definition 5.9 (Connection on principal bundle over differentiable stack). Let ${\mathscr{E}}_{G}$ be a principal $G$-bundle on a differentiable stack ${\mathscr{X}}$. A connection $\nabla$ on ${\mathscr{E}}_{G}$ consists of the data of a connection $\nabla_{u}$ on each principal $G$-bundle ${\mathscr{E}}_{G,u}$, where $u\,:\,U\,\longrightarrow\,{\mathscr{X}}$ is a smooth atlas for ${\mathscr{X}}$, which pulls back naturally with respect to each $2$-commutative diagram of the form $\xy\xymatrix{U\ar[dr]_{u}\ar[rr]^{\varphi}&&V\ar[dl]^{v}\\ &{\mathscr{X}.}&}\endxy$ A connection $\nabla$ on ${\mathscr{E}}_{G}$ is flat if it is integrable.
Definition 4.6. A differential $j$-form on the Lie groupoid $[X_{1}\rightrightarrows X_{0}]$ is a differential $j$-form $\omega$ on $X_{0}$ such that $H(s^{*}\omega)\,=\,H(t^{*}\omega)$.
Definition \thedef. The $\mathtt{i}$th principal 2-representation $\mathbf{P}_{\mathtt{i}}:\mathscr{C}\to\mathfrak{A}_{\mathbb{k}}$ of $\mathscr{C}$ is defined on objects $\mathtt{j}\in\mathscr{C}$ as $\mathbf{P}(\mathtt{j})=\mathscr{C}(\mathtt{i},\mathtt{j})$, on 1-morphisms $F$ as $\mathbf{P}(F)=F\circ-$, and on 2-morphisms $\alpha$ as $\mathbf{P}(\alpha)=\alpha\circ_{H}-$. Since $\mathscr{C}$ is a locally finitary 2-category, this is a finitary 2-representation.
Definition \thedef. Let $\mathscr{C}$ be a $G$-graded 2-category. We define the $G$-envelope 2-category $\hat{\mathscr{C}}$ of $\mathscr{C}$ by taking the same objects as $\mathscr{C}$, and defining each hom-category $\hat{\mathscr{C}}(\mathtt{i},\mathtt{j})$ as the $G$-envelope of the category $\mathscr{C}(\mathtt{i},\mathtt{j})$. We further require that composition respects the envelope; that is, for 1-morphisms $X\llbracket g\rrbracket$ and $Y\llbracket h\rrbracket$, $X\llbracket g\rrbracket\circ Y\llbracket h\rrbracket=(X\circ Y)\llbracket g+h\rrbracket$ wherever this makes sense. We also define horizontal and vertical composition of 2-morphisms as the obvious inheritance from composition in $\mathscr{C}$. If $\mathscr{C}$ is a locally $G$-graded finitary 2-category, then we say that its $G$-envelope is a locally $G$-finitary 2-category.
Definition \thedef. Let $A$ be a $G$-graded $\mathbb{k}$-algebra. We say that $A$ is $G$-graded-finite dimensional if it has a $G$-grading $A=\bigoplus\limits_{g\in G}A_{g}$ such that each $A_{g}$ is finite dimensional as a $\mathbb{k}$-vector space. In particular, this implies that $A_{0}$ is a finite dimensional $\mathbb{k}$-algebra.
Definition \thedef. Let $\mathbf{M}$ be a finitary 2-representation of $\mathscr{C}$. We say that $\mathbf{M}$ is transitive if for any $\mathtt{i}\in\mathscr{C}$ and any non-zero $X\in\mathbf{M}(\mathtt{i})$, $\mathbf{G}_{\mathbf{M}}(\{X\})$ is equivalent to $\mathbf{M}$.
Definition \thedef. The cyclotomic Khovanov-Lauda-Rouquier algebra $R^{\Lambda}(\beta)$ of weight $\beta$ at $\Lambda$ is defined as the quotient algebra $R^{\Lambda}(\beta)=\frac{R(\beta)}{R(\beta)a^{\Lambda}(x_{1})R(\beta)}$, with $R^{\Lambda}(0)=\mathbb{k}$. We note that $R^{\Lambda}(n)=\bigoplus\limits_{|\beta|=n}R^{\Lambda}(\beta)=\frac{R(n)}{R(n)% a^{\Lambda}(x_{1})R(n)}$.
Definition \thedef. Given an additive category $\mathcal{C}$, the injective fan Freyd abelianisation $\underline{\mathcal{C}}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is an additive category that is defined as follows: • Objects of $\underline{\mathcal{C}}$ are equivalence classes of tuples of the form $(X,k,Y_{i},f_{i})_{i\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}}$ where $X$ and the $Y_{i}$ are objects of $\mathcal{C}$, the $f_{i}$ are morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$, and $k$ is a non-negative integer such that $Y_{i}=0$ for $i>k$. Two tuples are equivalent if they only differ in the value of $k$. • A morphism from $(X,k,Y_{i},f_{i})$ to $(X^{\prime},k^{\prime},Y_{i}^{\prime},f^{\prime}_{i})$ is an equivalence class of tuples $(g,h_{ij})_{i,j\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}}$ where $g:X\to X^{\prime}$ and $h_{ij}:Y_{i}\to Y^{\prime}_{j}$ are morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$ such that $f^{\prime}_{i}g=\sum\limits_{j}h_{ji}f_{j}$ for each $i$, modulo the $(g,h_{ij})$ such that there exist $q_{i}:Y_{i}\to X^{\prime}$ with $\sum\limits_{i}q_{i}f_{i}=g$. • The identity morphisms are of the form $(\text{id}_{X},\delta_{ij}\text{id}_{Y_{i}})$ and composition is given by $(g^{\prime},h^{\prime}_{ij})\circ(g,h_{ij})=(g^{\prime}g,\sum\limits_{k}h^{% \prime}_{kj}h_{ik})$. The projective fan Freyd abelianisation is defined dually.
Definition \thedef. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a $G$-graded category. We define its $G$-envelope $\hat{\mathcal{C}}$ as a category with objects defined formally as symbols of the form $X\llbracket g\rrbracket$ where $X$ is an object of $\mathcal{C}$ and $g\in G$. For notational convenience we set $X\llbracket g\rrbracket\llbracket h\rrbracket:=X\llbracket g+h\rrbracket$. We set hom-spaces as $\operatorname{Hom}_{\hat{\mathcal{C}}}(X\llbracket g\rrbracket,Y\llbracket h% \rrbracket)\cong\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)\llbracket h-g\rrbracket$ with composition of morphisms is given by the obvious inheritance from $\mathcal{C}$. If $\mathcal{C}$ is a $G$-graded finitary category then we call $\hat{\mathcal{C}}$ a $G$-finitary category.
Definition \thedef. Let $\mathscr{C}$ be a locally finitary 2-category and $\mathbf{M}$ a 2-representation of $\mathscr{C}$. We say that $\mathbf{M}$ is 2-full if for any 1-morphisms in $\mathscr{C}$ the representation map $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathscr{C}}(F,G)\to\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathfrak{R}_{% \mathbb{k}}}(\mathbf{M}F,\mathbf{M}G)$ is surjective. For a $\mathscr{J}$-cell $\mathcal{J}$ of $\mathscr{C}$, we say $\mathbf{M}$ is $\mathcal{J}$-2-full if for every $F,G\in\mathcal{J}$, the representation map is surjective.
Definition \thedef. Let $\mathscr{C}$ be a locally $G$-finitary 2-category. We define a $G$-finitary 2-representation to be a strict $G$-graded 2-functor from $\mathscr{C}$ to $\mathfrak{A}_{\mathbb{k}}^{G\text{-gf}}$. An abelian 2-representation is a strict 2-functor from $\mathscr{C}$ to $\mathfrak{R}_{\mathbb{k}}$.
Definition \thedef. Let $\mathscr{C}$ be a locally weakly fiat 2-category and let $\mathcal{J}$ be a non-trivial $\mathscr{J}$-cell in $\mathscr{C}$. $\mathscr{C}$ is $\mathcal{J}$-simple if every non-trivial 2-ideal of $\mathscr{C}$ contains $\text{id}_{F}$ for some $F\in\mathcal{J}$.
Definition \thedef. Let $\mathscr{C}$ and $\mathscr{B}$ be locally $G$-finitary 2-categories. We say that a strict 2-functor $F:\mathscr{C}\to\mathscr{B}$ is a $G$-graded strict 2-functor if each component functor $F_{\mathtt{i},\mathtt{j}}:\mathscr{C}(\mathtt{i},\mathtt{j})\to\mathscr{B}(F% \mathtt{i},F\mathtt{j})$ is a $G$-graded functor.
Definition \thedef. For a 2-category $\mathscr{C}$ and a 2-ideal $\mathscr{I}$ of $\mathscr{C}$, we define the quotient 2-category $\mathscr{C}/\mathscr{I}$ as follows: the objects and 1-morphisms of $\mathscr{C}/\mathscr{I}$ are the same as those of $\mathscr{C}$ and the hom-sets between 1-morphisms are defined as $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathscr{C}/\mathscr{I}(\mathtt{i},\mathtt{j})}(F,G):=% \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathscr{C}(\mathtt{i},\mathtt{j})}(F,G)/\operatorname{Hom% }_{\mathscr{I}(\mathtt{i},\mathtt{j})}(F,G).$
